This memorandum was prepared by Fay, Spofford & Thorndike to provide a compilation of
existing conditions traffic findings for the Inner Belt/Brickbottom (IBBB) Area. Data presented
includes displays and tables intended to inform the work being performed on behalf of the City of
Somerville by the Goody Clancy Team in connection with the Adaptive Re-use Plan for the Area.
The Inner Belt/Brickbottom Area has the potential to be one of the greatest redevelopment stories
in the Boston Metropolitan Area. Its future land use and transportation are tightly linked. Our
premise in conducting the attached analysis is to provide a thorough understanding of the ‘state
of the circulation infrastructure’ to firm a solid foundation for subsequent study phases that will
address the safety and mobility issues identified.
Following is a summary of the contents of this memorandum:

i.b: Review of Existing Historic Studies and Data

page.text: Circulation features of the Inner Belt/Brickbottom Area (IBBB Area) have, and continue to be, the
subject of numerous studies. At the outset of this study, an inventory of existing historic studies
was undertaken and key transportation findings of the studies were summarized. A series of user-
friendly one-page summaries were prepared and are attached as Appendix I to this Existing
Conditions Analysis Technical Memorandum. Studies where circulation findings are summarized
include the following (organized by most recent):
Green Line Extension EIR/Preliminary Design (ongoing through 2020)
Metropolitan Area Planning Council’s Metro-Future Plan (2009)
Toward a Route 28 Corridor Transportation Plan: An Emerging Vision (December 2008)
Somerville Equitable Transit Oriented Development Strategy (May 2008)
Edge as Center International Urban Design Ideas by the Boston Society of Architects
Regional roadway access to the IBBB is very limited. I-93 has a single northbound off-ramp to
Washington Street. The McGrath Highway with a southbound exit to Somerville Avenue and full
access at Washington Street and a box tunnel connecting road between Somerville Avenue and
the frontage road to Washington Street. Washington Street provides east-west arterial access.
The impending Green Line Extension, including a new station serving the Inner Belt/Brickbottom
Area, according to latest projections is expected to occur no sooner than the year 2020. Potential
development in the Sullivan Square/ Rutherford Avenue part of Charlestown and the North Point
Area of Somerville and Cambridge has been in the news lately. As a part of this study, interviews
with the representatives of the City of Boston and Cambridge will be undertaken to obtain the
latest information on issues and perspective on the immediate areas adjacent to the IBBB Area
after meeting with the City of Somerville to frame the discussions with its community neighbors.
Meetings with MassDOT officials have already occurred and will continue as the ‘Grounding
The MBTA has signed a $22 million contract with HDR/Gilbane to undertake final design of the
Green Line Extension with Station openings scheduled to occur by the year 2020. The Green
Line Extension includes a new Brickbottom Station (potentially re-named the Cobble Hill Station)
at Washington Street. The Brickbottom Station requires the reconstruction of an existing railroad
bridge over Washington Street replacing it with a new station just south of Washington Street.
Two critical aspects of the design are relevant to the Inner Belt/Brickbottom Area study:
1) The location and design of the station and its pedestrian/bike/bus access features,
2) Design and screening of the new Green Line car storage and maintenance facility to
be located on the south/south east side of the Inner Belt Area just south of Third
Street and Inner Belt Road (Option L from the approved EIR).

page.text: A new team has recently been identified to begin long awaited work on the North Point
development, primarily located in the City of Cambridge, although Somerville also has a portion of
the area. The Plan that has been approved since 2003 has yet to develop. Relocation of the
Lechmere Station in Cambridge – i.e., the current northernmost station of the Green Line, should
serve as a strong catalyst for jumpstarting the North Point Area redevelopment.
To update the circulation analysis for the Inner Belt/Brickbottom Area, new field data was
collected. Within the context of the historical data, newly collected traffic data provides the
foundation for creating a circulation system that will maximize opportunities for redevelopment.

text.i: Existing Public Transportation & Visible Bike Storage Facilities

page.text: While lots of bus service does exist in the Inner Belt/Brickbottom Area, for all the criss-crossing
rails in the area, no passenger rail service are yet provided to the IBBB Area. However, Green
Line services are on the way. An impending Green Line Extension proposes construction of 7
new stations plus a relocated Lechmere Station in Cambridge. Ultimately, a Mystic Valley
Parkway/Route 16 Station in Medford will be the northwesterly terminal, with Somerville Stations
including a Brickbottom/ Washington Street station, plus stations at Union Square, Gilman
Square, Lowell Street, and Ball Street on the Somerville/Medford border. The new Green Line
Brickbottom Station will provide the Inner Belt/Brickbottom Area with excellent connections to the
entire MBTA light rail and rapid transit system. This will make the IBBB Area transit-accessible to
a much larger population base for both existing residents and future employers.

Level of Service (LOS) is a commonly accepted measure of effectiveness of peak hour traffic
operating conditions identified in the Highway Capacity Manual (HCM, 2000 Edition). LOS
accounts for such factors as automobile and truck volumes, roadway capacity, speeds,
pedestrians and bikes, grades, traffic control devices, the progression of vehicular traffic flow
along an arterial roadway, roadway types, roadway widths and geometric layouts, as well as
anticipated delays. Levels of service range from A, the optimal condition, to F, the condition
where traffic demands are beyond capacity or create excessive delay conditions.
At LOS E and LOS F, roadway or intersection operations are
typically regarded as ‘undesirable’. Thus, LOS D has typically
become a threshold between desirable and undesirable peak
hour traffic operations. When intersections become

Traffic operations at unsignalized two-way stop controlled intersections are given LOS rankings
based on conflicting traffic flows and anticipated control delays related to conflicting minor
movement traffic flows. These conflicting flows are the vehicular turning movements at
intersections that potentially must yield the right-of-way to other traffic movements at an
intersection. Examples of these conflicting movements would be left turns from a major street to
a minor side street (across the opposing flow of traffic), or left and right turns from a minor street
or side street to the major street.
At unsignalized intersections, LOS measures are only given for conflicting movements. An LOS
ranking at an unsignalized intersection is determined by calculating the average total delay in
seconds per vehicle. Total delay is the total elapsed time from when a vehicle stops at the end of
a queue until the time when that vehicle departs from the stop line and enters the traffic stream.
This includes the time required for the vehicle to travel from the last-in-queue position to the first-
in-queue position. The average total delay for any particular minor movement is a function of the
traffic demand flow rate and the capacity of the approach. Put another way, average total delay
is a function of traffic volumes and the physical geometry of the intersection in terms of number of
From Table 2.3.2 on the previous page, LOS A, the optimal level of service at signalized or
unsignalized intersections is defined as an average total delay of 10 seconds or less per vehicle.
For unsignalized intersections, according to the 2000 HCM, total delay of 50 seconds per vehicle
is the break point between LOS E (capacity) and LOS F (congestion). LOS F exists when
average control delays exceed 50 seconds for side street stop or yield controlled vehicles. This
becomes a safety issue when the volume to capacity ratio for the side-street movement exceeds
1 and the impeded movements have insufficient gaps to conduct a crossing or turning movement
to or from a major street.
Signalized intersections have different criteria for acceptable total delay than unsignalized
intersections. At signalized intersections, higher total delay values are generally considered to be
more acceptable to motorists than at unsignalized intersections in exchange for the ability to
make the desired movements with minimal conflict when the approach is served. While the
LOS A criteria is the same as at unsignalized intersections, LOS B-F involve additional seconds
of total delay. For example, the worst case LOS F at signalized intersections involves 30
seconds more than LOS F criteria for unsignalized intersections.
Another term used in the analysis of traffic operations is “volume-to-capacity ratio” or, in
abbreviated form, “V/C”. V/C is the ratio of actual flow rate to its theoretical capacity for a given
transportation facility or, more specifically in this case, for a given traffic movement within an
intersection. Sustainable values of V/C range from 1.0 when the traffic flow rate equals capacity
to zero when the flow rate is zero. V/C values above 1.0 indicate an excess of demand over
capacity (the new 2010 HCM, not yet approved, does not allow V/C’s to exceed 1.0). In layman’s
terms, a V/C value greater than 1.0 indicates that more vehicles want to make a particular traffic
movement within an intersection during a specific length of time than the intersection has the
capacity to accommodate during that same time period. When V/C’s exceed 1.0, motorists
become frustrated and are more inclined to aggressive and hazardous driving behavior and
merge into traffic with than acceptable gaps in traffic, run red lights, or pay less attention to
pedestrians and cyclists who may be traversing the area.
Still another term used in intersection analysis is queue length. A queue is a line of vehicles
waiting to be processed through an intersection. Queue length is determined by multiplying the
number of vehicles in a queue by an average vehicle length and average gap between vehicles.
Typically, this is assumed at 25 feet per passenger car. Traffic operations including levels of
service and queues were analyzed using the SYNCHRO Version 7software. SYNCHRO provides
analyses consistent with the HCM 2000, the current capacity methodology approved by Federal

To assess safety in the area, crash data was obtained from MassDOT Highway Division
for the 2007-2009 three-year period. Not all crashes are reported, as ‘fender bender’ type crashes
less than $1,000 in property damage and non-injury are often under-reported. Crashes were
identified by location and type within the Area illustrated on Figure 2.3.8. Crash data summarized
on Figure 2.3.8 identifies geo-coded 3-year total reported crashes. Injury crashes and the
number of pedestrian and bicycle crashes by location are highlighted.
MassDOT crash rate work sheets were compiled for those locations that experienced 4
or more reported crashes or 2 or more reported injury crashes. Of the locations identified, two
were found to have crash rates higher than those for signalized or unsignalized intersections
statewide or in MassDOT District 4 – Washington Street at the McGrath Highway Ramps and
CTPS modeled base 2009 base year mode share data was reviewed. Figure 2.3.9
summarizes CTPS modeled 2009 base year per person data for the three traffic analysis zones
that comprise the IBBB Area. From Figure 2.3.9, more people end up driving to the IBBB Area as
a destination than leaving from the IBBB Area as an origin. More than 83% drive to the Area,
while nearly 35% of existing residents either use public transportation or walk. While sidewalks
are provided on all public roadways in the area, crossings at wide intersections are impaired due
to the absence of specific pedestrian controls. Sidewalks under the railroad bridge over
Washington Street at the future Brickbottom Station are dark and not pedestrian friendly.
Additionally, Figures 2.3.10 and 2.3.11 were prepared to identify critical existing mobility
and safety issues in the IBBB Area. Figure 2.3.10 summarizes auto/truck vehicle mobility issues
and safety deficiencies, while Figure 2.3.11 summarizes pedestrian, bike, and bus circulation
deficiencies in the IBBB Area. From a sub-regional mobility perspective, IBBB circulation, at this
time, is wholly dependent on how well Washington Street is able to function to provide access to
its adjoining parcels east of the future Green Line light rail corridor. There is no east-west
redundancy of roadways with pedestrian and bike circulation facilities to share modal burdens
concentrated on Washington Street east of the Green Line. Resolving this circulation constraint
presents a significant challenge to the IBBB Area and impending adaptive reuse plans.
